    <subsection>
        <title>An Introduction to Different Types of Numbers</title>
        <p>When we talk about <em>how many</em> of something that we have, it often makes sense use different types of numbers. For example, it would be difficult to have <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> of a dollar. (Even if we can conceptualize this as <m>33\frac{1}{3}</m> cents, we don't actually have currency to represent <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> cent.) As another example, what would it mean to have <m>-2</m> apples? We might treat this as owing someone else two apples, but we still couldn't actually hold <m>-2</m> apples in our hand. Both of these examples highlight the need for different types of numbers. We'll classify various sets of numbers below.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Different Number Sets</title>

        <list>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Natural Numbers</title>
                    <p>When we count, we begin: <m>1, 2, 3, \dots</m> and continue on in that pattern. These numbers are known as <term>natural numbers</term>.</p>
                    <p>Set of Natural Numbers: <m>\{1,2,3,\dots \}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Whole Numbers</title>
                    <p>If we also include zero with our counting numbers, then we have the set of <term>whole numbers</term>.</p>
                    <p>Set of Whole Numbers: <m>\{0,1,2,3,\dots \}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Integers</title>
                    <p>Once we also include the negatives of every whole number, then we have the set of <term>integers</term>.</p>
                    <p>Set of Integers: <m>\{\dots,-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3,\dots \}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Rational Numbers</title>
                    <p>Any number that <em>can</em> be written as a ratio of integers belongs to the set of <term>rational numbers</term>.</p>
                    <p>Set of Rational Numbers: <m>\left\{\frac{a}{b} \mid a\ \textrm{and}\ b\ \textrm{are integers}\right\}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Irrational Numbers</title>
                    <p>Any number that <em>cannot</em> be written as a ratio of integers belongs to the set of <term>irrational numbers</term>. Some examples include <m>\pi, \sqrt{15}, e, \frac{3\pi}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{8}}{2}</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Real Numbers</title>
                    <p>Any number that can be written on a number line, which includes all rational and irrational numbers, is a <term>real number</term>.</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </list>
    
        <remark>
            <p>It's key to note that any number that <em>can</em> be written as a ratio of integers is in this set, so all integers are included in this set. (As, for example, <m>-4</m> can be written as <m>\frac{-4}{1}</m>. Rational numbers also include <term>terminating decimals</term>, such as <m>0.245</m>. To see why this is true, note that we verbally say <m>0.245</m> as <q>two hundred and forty-five thousandths,</q> which is <m>\frac{245}{1000}</m>. Lastly, <term>repeating decimals</term> are also rational numbers. We denote these with the repetend symbol, such as <m>0.535353... = 0.\bar{53}</m>. This can be shown to be equal to the fraction <m>\frac{53}{99}</m>.</p>
        </remark>    

