        <todo>Make this a WeBWorK problem</todo>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Identify the smallest set of numbers that is appropriate for modeling each scenario. (Possible sets include: natural numbers, whole numbers, integers, rational numbers, and irrational numbers).</p>
                <p><ol>
                    <li>The number of people in a math class that play the ukulele.</li>
                    <li>The length around the edge of a donut with a radius  <quantity><mag>1.5</mag><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.</li>
                    <li>The proportion of people in a math class that have a cat.</li>
                    <li>The number of people who purchased tickets for well-attended Timbers soccer game.</li>
                    <li>The total revenue (in dollars) generated for ticket sales at a Timbers soccer game.</li>
                    <li>The difference in age between two siblings.</li>
                </ol></p>    
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Identify the smallest set of numbers that is appropriate for modeling each scenario.</p>
                <p><ol>
                    <li>Whole numbers. The number of people who play the ukulele could be <m>0,1,2,\dots</m>. If we wanted to restrict this even further, we could see that the set <m>\{0,1,2,\dots,n\}</m> where <m>n</m> is the number of students in the class.</li>
                    <li>Irrational numbers. The circumference of a circle always <m>2\pi</m> times the radius of the circle.</li>
                    <li>Rational numbers. This proportion will be a ratio of integers, as both the number of people in the class total and the number of people who have a cat are integers.</li>
                    <li>Natural numbers.We know that the number of people must be a counting number, and since the game was <q>well attended</q> we know that zero is not included.</li>
                    <li>Rational numbers. The total revenue will be some number of dollars and cents, such as <m>\$ </m>, which is a terminating decimal and thus a rational number.</li>
                    <li>Integers. Depending on how we compute this difference, it could be either a positive or negative counting number (or zero, should they be twins).</li>
                </ol></p>    
            </solution>
        </example>
